    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Orobus hispanicus improperly include causing diarrhea, inducing vomiting, inducing nausea, causing abdominal pain and inducing vomiting. This is due to its toxic and irritating properties which can cause gastrointestinal irritation leading to these symptoms. The plant contains alkaloids such as orobammine and oroborine which can be toxic if ingested in large amounts. Ingestion of Orobus hispanicus can lead to gastrointestinal upset, including vomiting, nausea and diarrhea, as the body attempts to eliminate the toxins. Prolonged exposure to its toxic compounds can cause abdominal pain and may lead to more severe health issues if left untreated.",
    "uses": "Orobus hispanicus has been used in traditional medicine, particularly in the Iberian Peninsula, to treat various ailments. Its leaves and flowers are said to possess anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties. The plant is also believed to have antiseptic and antibacterial properties, which may help in wound healing. However, more research is needed to confirm the efficacy and safety of Orobus hispanicus for medicinal use. Its potential health benefits also highlight the importance of continued studies on this plant species.",
    "taxonomy": "Orobus hispanicus is a species of flowering plant in the legume family, Fabaceae. It belongs to the genus Orobus, which is a small genus of annual or biennial legumes. The species is further classified under the subfamily Faboideae, which is one of the largest subfamilies within the Fabaceae family. The classification of Orobus hispanicus reflects its botanical relationship to other legumes, such as clover and peas. Orobus hispanicus is native to the Iberian Peninsula in southwestern Europe.",
    "benefits": "Orobus hispanicus has been traditionally used in folk medicine due to its potential health benefits. The plant contains various compounds that may have antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties, which could contribute to its health benefits. Some studies suggest that Orobus hispanicus may help to protect against oxidative stress and cell damage. Additionally, the plant's extracts may have antimicrobial and antifungal properties, which could aid in the treatment of certain infections. Further research is needed to fully understand the health benefits of Orobus hispanicus.",
    "parts": "Orobus hispanicus. The medicinal parts of Orobus hispanicus are not well-documented, but like other members of the legume family, it may have some medicinal properties due to its alkaloid content. However, the specific parts of the plant used for medicinal purposes, if any, are unknown. Further research is required to determine the exact medicinal properties and uses of Orobus hispanicus. Some traditional uses of Orobus hispanicus may be found in local folklore, but these are not supported by scientific evidence.",
    "intro": "Orobus hispanicus, also known as Spanish vetchling, is a perennial herbaceous plant belonging to the legume family (Fabaceae). The plant has been traditionally used for its medicinal properties, offering health benefits such as anti-inflammatory and antioxidant effects, which may help alleviate symptoms of various conditions, including digestive issues and skin problems. The bioactive constituents of Orobus hispanicus include flavonoids, saponins, and phenolic acids, which contribute to its therapeutic properties. In herbal medicine, Orobus hispanicus is commonly prepared in the form of infusions, decoctions, or tinctures to support digestive health and soothe skin irritations."
